#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Theo Agent OS Glass v0.5.8 - Noted by Theo - 2026-06-13.

v0.5.0 adds live-state sync for the admin door: visibility-aware polling that
only re-renders on real change and never clobbers an open run detail, artifact
preview, or action feedback. Adds a sync indicator, manual Refresh, and a
Live/Pause toggle. Server actions stay admin-gated + same-origin as before.

v0.5.1 adds an admin-gated `/control/` Railway proxy to the Spartacus
OpenClaw gateway Control UI, including WebSocket upgrade tunneling. This avoids
new Railway resource provisioning while keeping Spartacus token/device auth as
the real authority.

v0.5.2 preserves deep links after successful admin login, so `/control/#token=...`
continues to the Control UI instead of dropping Coach on the Glass root.

v0.5.3 turns the one-off Control proxy into a closed node registry. Spartacus
stays live, `/control/` remains a compatibility alias, and
`/control/<node>/` becomes the canonical shape for multi-node Mission Control.

v0.5.4 makes Spartacus the explicit VPS proof-of-concept path. Glass now probes
configured Control nodes from the web tier and shows Spartacus as the reference
remote node, so the POC is visible without needing a physical machine.

v0.5.5 turns the Control tab into a Spartacus-first Jarvis / Agent OS panel:
one proof chain, clear operator entry routes, app-layer gateway response checks,
and future nodes demoted to planned reachability instead of competing with the
VPS POC.

v0.5.6 adds the first Theo OS Mission Control cockpit: left workspace/agent
rail, center live mission timeline, right details rail, and an inert composer
stub. It reuses the existing `/api/state` data and keeps Glass read-only for
operations, with Spartacus actions limited to refresh/deep-link routes.

v0.5.7 adds the first cockpit-native action receipt: an admin-gated, read-only
Spartacus refresh action that forces the existing gateway proof probe and writes
a visible receipt into the Mission Control timeline/right rail.

v0.5.8 fixes the mobile cockpit chrome after Coach's screenshot review: desktop
rails collapse on phone widths, safe-area spacing keeps browser/system overlays
off the interface, and a fixed bottom navigation bar exposes primary sections
with a More sheet for overflow.

Localhost-only Mission Control for Shot 2. Glass reads Foundry run envelopes
and exposes only two tiny write lanes: memory proposal verdict queue entries
and manual security checklist attestations.

Railway review mode is intentionally read-only. It exists so Coach and Fable
can inspect Shot 2 through a stable URL without exposing local operator writes.
"""

